---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import HelpCallout from "../../components/HelpCallout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Youth"
  description="Worried about a young person's gambling? Signs to watch for, how to start the conversation, and how to take care of yourself — for parents, family, and friends."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/family-and-friends">← Family &amp; friends</a>
      </p>
      <h1>Youth</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Worried about a young person's gambling? Here's how to recognize the
        signs and start the conversation — without making it worse.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <p>
        Gambling for young people in 2026 doesn't look the way it did a
        generation ago. Most kids who get into trouble aren't sneaking into
        casinos — they're paying for loot boxes inside a video game, betting on
        sports through a friend's account, or playing social-casino apps that
        look exactly like real slot machines. The harm is real. The entry point
        is the phone in their pocket.
      </p>
      <p>
        You don't need to be a clinician to help. The most powerful thing you
        can do is start a calm, curious conversation — and keep it going.
      </p>

      <h2>Signs to watch for</h2>
      <p>
        No single sign means a young person is in trouble. Patterns matter more
        than any one moment. These signs often show up together:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Sudden interest in checking sports scores or game outcomes at
          unusual hours, especially late at night.</li>
        <li>Asking for money to buy things inside a game more often than they
          used to, and spending more than they used to.</li>
        <li>Secrecy with the phone or laptop — turning the screen, locking the
          device, clearing browser history.</li>
        <li>Big mood swings tied to game outcomes — elated after a win,
          withdrawn or angry after a loss.</li>
        <li>Falling behind on schoolwork, dropping activities they used to care
          about, or skipping meals.</li>
        <li>Borrowing money from siblings or friends and being vague about why.</li>
        <li>Talking about "earning" money through games, sports picks, or
          predictions in ways that don't add up.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to bring it up</h2>
      <p>
        Lead with curiosity, not accusation. The goal of the first conversation
        isn't to fix the problem — it's to keep the door open so there's a
        second conversation.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Pick a low-pressure moment.</strong> Driving in the car, on
          a walk, doing dishes together. Not after a fight, not at the dinner
          table with everyone watching.</li>
        <li><strong>Start with what you've noticed, not what you've concluded.</strong>
          "I noticed you've been on the betting app a lot this week" lands
          differently than "You have a gambling problem."</li>
        <li><strong>Ask open-ended questions.</strong> "What's it been like for
          you lately?" leaves room for honesty. "Are you gambling?" leads to
          one-word answers.</li>
        <li><strong>Listen more than you talk.</strong> If they push back, don't
          argue. You're not trying to win — you're trying to learn.</li>
        <li><strong>Name your concern without ultimatums.</strong> "I love you
          and I'm worried" is enough. "Stop or you're grounded forever" closes
          the door.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>What not to do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Don't pay off their debts.</strong> Covering what they owe
          tells them the rescue is automatic. Hard as it is, the consequences
          are often what makes the problem real to them.</li>
        <li><strong>Don't take away the phone forever.</strong> A full
          confiscation usually backfires. They'll find another way, and you'll
          lose visibility into what's happening.</li>
        <li><strong>Don't shame them in public.</strong> Public callouts at
          family gatherings, in front of friends, or on social media can
          deepen isolation and raise the risk of self-harm.</li>
        <li><strong>Don't make it about your disappointment.</strong> "I'm so
          disappointed in you" puts the burden of your feelings on them, on
          top of the burden they're already carrying.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>If a major loss or disclosure just happened</h2>
      <p>
        Family members often have a short window — sometimes only a few hours —
        when a young person is willing to talk after something big has come
        out in the open. If you're in that window now, the next three days
        matter.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Take a breath before you react.</strong> The first ten
          minutes set the tone for everything that comes next.</li>
        <li><strong>Get the immediate-harm picture.</strong> Are they safe? Is
          anyone they owe money to making threats? Are there strangers (in-game
          or otherwise) involved?</li>
        <li><strong>Don't make permanent decisions in the first 24 hours.</strong>
          No new accounts, no closed accounts, no big ultimatums until you've
          slept on it.</li>
        <li><strong>Tell one other adult you trust.</strong> A spouse, a
          sibling, a school counselor, the family doctor. You don't have to
          carry this alone.</li>
        <li><strong>Within 72 hours, talk to a professional.</strong> The
          school counselor, the pediatrician, or the helpline below are good
          first calls.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>About suicide risk</h2>
      <p>
        Young people in serious gambling trouble are at significantly higher
        risk for suicidal thoughts and attempts than their peers. Naming this
        directly isn't alarmist — it's protective. If a young person says
        anything that sounds like they don't want to be here, don't try to
        talk them out of it. Take it seriously, stay with them, and call or
        text <strong>988</strong> (the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline) or the
        national helpline below.
      </p>

      <h2>Taking care of yourself</h2>
      <p>
        You can't talk a young person out of a gambling problem in a single
        conversation, and you can't fix it by trying harder. What you can do
        is stay grounded enough to keep showing up for them — and that's
        harder than it sounds.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Gam-Anon</strong> is a free, peer-led group for families and
        friends of people with gambling problems. Meetings are confidential,
        held in person and online, and members are people whose loved ones
        have been where yours is now. There's no cost and no requirement to
        share. You can find a meeting at
        <a href="https://www.gam-anon.org/" rel="noopener">gam-anon.org</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you're starting to feel symptoms of your own — sleep loss, weight
        changes, panic, persistent dread — talk to your own doctor. Caring
        for someone with a gambling problem is its own kind of strain, and
        it's legitimate to get help for it.
      </p>

      <HelpCallout />
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
